{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489318"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.14,0.72,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52652"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/633"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38015"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52652"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness. He is admitted to hospital with a diagnosis of haemorrhagic stroke. A CT scan shows a large 85 mL haematoma with moderate contrast extravasation. He has a medical history of recent back pain for which he has been taking paracetamol. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. There is right-sided motor weakness in his arm, hand, and leg. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 128 g/L (130-175) and platelet count of 130 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450). His serum biochemistry is shown (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/ccd2a69c-e526-40ad-a4fa-b923776c9755.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs part of the rehabilitation program, consideration must be given to prophylaxis against venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest contraindication to pharmacological VTE prophylaxis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The platelet count","The renal function","The haemorrhagic stroke","The paracetamol use","The impaired mobility"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhagic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E is the strongest contraindication to pharmacological venous thromboembolism (VTE) prophylaxis. This patient has a large, acute intracerebral haemorrhage with evidence of ongoing bleeding (contrast extravasation on CT), which significantly increases the risk of haematoma expansion if anticoagulants are administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplatelet count\u003C/strong\u003E, while slightly low, is not a strong contraindication to VTE prophylaxis. Mild thrombocytopenia (platelet count \u0026gt;50 x 10^9/L) is generally not considered an absolute contraindication to prophylactic anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal function\u003C/strong\u003E appears to be within normal limits based on the creatinine level provided. Therefore, it does not pose a contraindication to VTE prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent \u003Cstrong\u003Eparacetamol use\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication to VTE prophylaxis. Paracetamol does not significantly affect blood coagulation or interact with anticoagulants in a clinically meaningful way.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired mobility\u003C/strong\u003E due to stroke is actually an indication for VTE prophylaxis rather than a contraindication. Immobility increases the risk of deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism, which is why VTE prophylaxis is considered in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with acute haemorrhagic stroke, the risk of haematoma expansion with pharmacological anticoagulation generally outweighs the benefit of VTE prevention in the first few days. Mechanical prophylaxis methods, such as intermittent pneumatic compression devices, are often used instead. The timing of initiating pharmacological prophylaxis in these patients remains controversial and depends on various factors including haematoma size, stability, and overall clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For all hospitalised patients, consideration must be given to VTE prophylaxis.","Recent haemorrhagic stroke is a strong contraindication to pharmacological VTE prophylaxis due to the risk of haematoma expansion.","Large haematoma volume and contrast extravasation on initial CT are risk factors for haematoma expansion in acute haemorrhagic stroke."],"references":["Yogendrakumar V, Lun R, Khan F, Salottolo K, Lacut K, Catriona G, et al. Venous thromboembolism prevention in intracerebral hemorrhage: A systematic review and network meta-analysis. Plus One. 2020;15(6). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32579570/","Kappelle LJ. Preventing Deep Vein Thrombosis After Stroke: Strategies and Recommendations. Curr Treat Options Neurol. 2011;13(6):629-35. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3207135/","Sandercock PA, Counsell C, Kane EJ. Anticoagulants for acute ischaemic stroke. Cochrane Databse Syst Rev. 2015; 2015(3). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25764172/","Naidech, AM. Intracranial haemorrhage. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2011; 184(9); 998-1006. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22167847/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17786"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17786"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ccd2a69c-e526-40ad-a4fa-b923776c9755.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ccd2a69c-e526-40ad-a4fa-b923776c9755.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":386}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T16:31:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T16:31:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"633"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52652"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",